{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:06:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.01,0.34,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51603"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3151"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"84"},{"type":"contributions","id":"85"},{"type":"contributions","id":"86"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44068"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51603"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother who reports she cannot control him anymore. His mother states that he does not pay attention to her and does not follow her rules, such as putting his toys away before watching television. These behavioural issues have been ongoing for more than six months. She also complains that her son is unable to concentrate on any task lasting longer than a few minutes. For instance, he is unable to finish a meal completely without running up and down the corridor. The teachers at his preschool report that he is more active than his peers and frequently disrupts the class. He is also very forgetful during class and the teachers are struggling to make him concentrate on specific tasks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe was born at term via vaginal delivery without any complications. His medical history includes acute otitis media three years ago. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has met all his developmental milestones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The child is able to turn his head and make eye contact when his name is called. However, he does not answer direct questions when he is preoccupied with playing with the toys in the office. He often interrupts the conversation between his mother and the doctor, and demands to go outside and play. There are no other abnormalities in his physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hearing aids","Fluvoxamine","Sertraline","Methylphenidate","Behaviour therapy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with symptoms consistent with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). There is evidence of impulsivity, hyperactivity, distractibility and inattention in two settings - both his preschool and at home. These symptoms have been persisting for longer than six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBehaviour therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is considered first-line therapy for ADHD in preschool children. This therapy includes creation of a low-stimulus environment, providing support for learning difficulties, and parental training. It is preferred as the initial treatment due to its better tolerability and fewer side effects compared to medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylphenidate\u003C/strong\u003E is a stimulant medication used in the treatment of ADHD. However, it should be trialled only when behavioural therapy is ineffective, particularly in young children. This is because stimulant medications can potentially affect growth and have other side effects that may be problematic in young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluvoxamine\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in children with obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD), which manifests as persistent recurring thoughts, urges and obsessions that lead to ritualistic behaviours or compulsions. This child does not present with any symptoms of OCD and should not be given fluvoxamine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in the treatment of major depressive disorder (MDD) and disruptive mood dysregulation disorder (DMDD). However, this child does not present with symptoms of MDD such as depressed or irritable mood. Likewise, this child does not present with extreme irritability and anger with recurrent angry outbursts that are consistent with DMDD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHearing aids\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in this case. This child has no evidence of hearing loss since he is responsive when his name is called and has met all his developmental milestones. The history of acute otitis media three years ago is unlikely to have caused significant hearing impairment, as there are no ongoing concerns about his hearing mentioned in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, behaviour therapy is the most appropriate initial management for this child with suspected ADHD. It provides a non-pharmacological approach that can be effective in managing ADHD symptoms in young children, without the potential side effects associated with medication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Behaviour therapy should be the initial treatment offered to children with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) due to better tolerability and fewer side effects compared to medication.","Stimulant medications for ADHD, such as methylphenidate, can potentially affect growth and should be considered only after behaviour therapy has been tried."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association. Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition (DSM-5), American Psychiatric Association, Arlington 2013","May T, Birch E, Chaves K, Cranswick N, Culnane E, Delaney J, Derrick M, Eapen V, Edlington C, Efron D, Ewais T. The Australian evidence-based clinical practice guideline for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2023 Aug;57(8):1101-16."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-27T11:35:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-27T11:37:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51603"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9